sols:
We have that

\begin{align*}x(t)^2+2y(t)^2=9\end{align*}

and we want to find dy/dt when x=1, y=2 and dx/dt=3. Therefore, we
implicitly differentiate and isolate for dy/dt,

\begin{align*}
2x\frac{\textrm{d}x}{\textrm{d}t}+4y\frac{\textrm{d}y}{\textrm{d}t}&=0\\
\frac{\textrm{d}y}{\textrm{d}t}&=-\frac{x}{2y}\frac{\textrm{d}x}{\textrm{d}t}.\end{align*}

We then sub in x=1, y=2, and dx/dt=3 to get that

\begin{align*}\left.\frac{\textrm{d}y}{\textrm{d}t}\right|_{x=1,y=2}=-\frac{1}{4}(3)=-\frac{3}{4}\end{align*}

and so we conclude that the y-coordinate is changing at -3/4 kilometers
per minute at that moment.

hints:
Here x and y are functions of time, so we have the \textbf{implicit
relation}

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x(t)^2+2y(t)^2=9.\end{align*}
